      h5.card-title.card1-title 
        a(NAME='firmata') Installing Firmata on the Arduino Uno 
        br
        span(style='font-size: small;')
          a(href='#contents') Table of contents
      .card-body.card1-body
        p.card1-text In the 
          a(href='/tutorial/setupRPi#arduino', target='_blank') previous tutorial
          | , you learned how install the programming Integrated Development Environment (IDE) for the Arduino
          | and tested making one of the on-board LEDs blink. The Arduino IDE is a very elegant and powerful 
          | programming environment that is based on the C++ language. The C++ language can be a bit daunting 
          | for beginners and is overkill for many applications. Instead of beginning with using the Arduino IDE, 
          | we will in this tutorial install a software package called 
          a(href='https://github.com/firmata/arduino', target='_blank') Firmata
          | . This software package will allow us to communicate directly to the Arduino from Node-Red running 
          | on the device message adapter through the serial port. Of course the trade-off will be speed and the 
          | ability to use interrupts but this should not bother us for most applications and we revisit these 
          | features in future tutorials. 
          br
          | To install Firmata on the Arduino Uno, connect the serial port of the Arduino Uno to one of the serial 
          | ports of Raspberry Pi that you set up in the previous section. Open the Arduino IDE on the Raspberry Pi. 
          | Make sure you select the correct board (Arduino Uno) under Tools->Board->Arduino/Genuino Uno menu item 
          | and the correct port under Tools->Port->/dev/ttyACM0. Load the Firmata sketch into the Arduino IDE by 
          | selecting File->Examples->Firmata->StandardFirmata
          | Upload the sketch to the Arduino Uno using  upload button on the IDE.
        p 
